      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>Q. How risky is aflatoxin, a toxic carcinogen that can grow on peanuts, for American consumers?</p>
        <p>A. ''The short answer is that aflatoxin is of very little concern,'' said Donna L. Scott, a food scientist who is a senior extension associate at Cornell.</p>
        <p>First, Ms. Scott said, ''Aflatoxin is produced by the fungus Aspergillus flavus, and most Americans, even the very poor, don't eat moldy food, because it tastes bad.'' Documented human aflatoxin problems usually occur in tropical countries, where the wet climate is conducive to mold growth, or in extremely poor ones, where people are forced to eat any food they can get.</p>
        <p>Second, humans are much less affected by aflatoxin than animals, especially some birds, Ms. Scott said. Even someone who tried to commit suicide with aflatoxin, a lab worker, did not die or suffer much long-term harm, she said. It causes liver cancer in animals, but a big study of diet in China found no link between it and human liver cancer, except in those who had had hepatitis B.</p>
        <p>Third, Ms. Scott said, the United States Department of Agriculture works with all big farmers to monitor all crops, like grains and peanuts, that are susceptible to mold. The U.S.D.A. designed a machine that kicks out suspicious peanuts, and even if you get a moldy one, Ms. Scott said, chances are it is a different kind of mold. As for peanut butter, big producers test both raw materials and finished batches for aflatoxin.</p>
        <p>C. CLAIBORNE RAY</p>
      </block>
